\begin_layout Chapter*
9.1 Problems of Testing Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In example 8.3.1 on page 473, we were interested in whether or not the mean
 log-rainfall 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 from seeded clouds was greater than some constant, specifically 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 Hypothesis testing problems are similar in nature to the decision problem
 of Example 8.3.1.
 In general, hypothesis testing concerns trying to decide whether a parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 lies in one subset of the parameter space or in its complemet.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is one-dimensional, at least one of the two subsets will typically be an
 interval, possibly degenerate.
 In this section, we introduct the notation and some common methodology
 associated with hypothesis testing.
 We also demonstrate an equivalence between hypothesis tests and confidence
 intervals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
The Null and Alternative Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a statistical problem involving a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 whose value is unknown but must lie in a certain parameter space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose now that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 can be partitioned into two disjoint subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, and the statistician is interested in whether 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 or in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall let 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 denote hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 denote the hypothesis that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\Omega_{1}.$
\end_inset

Since subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}\cup\Omega_{1}=\Omega$
\end_inset

, exactly one of hypotheses 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 must be true.
 The statistician must decide which of the hypotheses 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 appears to be true.
 A problem of this type, in which there are only two possible decisions,
 is called a problem of 
\series bold
testing hypotheses
\series default
.
 If the statistician makes the wrong decisions, he might suffer a certain
 loss or pay a certain cost.
 In many problems, he will have an opportunity to observe some data before
 he has to make his decision, and the observed values will provide him with
 information about the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 A procedure for deciding which hypothesis to choose is called a
\series bold
 test procedure or simple a test
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our discussion up to this point, we have treated the hypotheses 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 on an equal basis.
 In most problems, however, the two hypotheses are treated quite differently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
9.1.1.
 Null and Alternative Hypotheses/Reject.
 The hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
null hypothesis 
\emph default
and hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
alternative hypothesis.
 
\emph default
When performing a test, if we decide that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, we are said to reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If we decide that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 we are said not to reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The terminology referring to the decisions in Definition 9.1.1 is asymetric
 with regard to the null and alternative hypotheses.
 We shall retrurn to this point later in the section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Simple and Composite Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},...,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 form a random sample from a distribution for which the p.d.f.
 or the p.f.
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x|\theta)$
\end_inset

 , where the value of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 must lie in the parameter space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint sets with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}\cup\Omega_{1}=\Omega$
\end_inset

; and ot os desired to test the following hypotheses:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{0}:\theta\in\Omega_{0},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{1}:\theta\in\Omega_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 may contain just a single value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 or it might be a larger set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Simple and Composite Hypotheses.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 contains just a single value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a simple hypothesis.
 If the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 contains more than one value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a composite hypothesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under a simple hypothesis, the distribution of the observations is completely
 specified.
 Under a composite hypothesis, it is specified only that the distribution
 of the observations belongs to a certain class.
 For example, a simple null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 must have the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{0}:\theta=\theta_{0}\text{ (9.1.1)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
9.1.3.
 One-sided and Two-sided Hypotheses.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 be a one-dimensional parameter.
 One-sided null hypotheses are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:\theta\le\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:\theta\geq\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, with the corresponding one-sided alternative hypotheses being 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:\theta>\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:\theta<\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 When the null hypothesis is simple, such as (9.1.1), the alternative hypothesis
 is usually two-sided, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:\theta\neq\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a problem in which we wish to test the following hypotheses:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{0}:\theta\in\Omega_{0},\text{ and }H_{1}:\theta\in\Omega_{1}\text{ (9.1.3)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that before the statistician has to decide which hypothesis to choose,
 she can observe a random sample 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X_{1},...,X_{n})$
\end_inset

 drawn from a distribution that involves the unknown parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 We shall let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 denote the sample space of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

dimensional random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the set of all possible values of the random sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a problem of this type, the statistician can specify a test procedure
 by partitioning the sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 into two subsets.
 One subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 contains the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 for which she will reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

, and the other subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 contains the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 for which she will not reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
9.1.4.
 Critical Region.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 defined above is called the critical region of the test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, a test procedure is determined by specifying the critical region
 of the test.
 The complement of the critical region must then contain all outcomes for
 which 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 will not be rejected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In most hypothesis-testing problems, the critical region is defined in terms
 of a statistic, 
\begin_inset Formula $T=r(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
9.1.5.
 Test Statistic/Rejection Region.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a random sample from a distribution that depends on a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T=r(X)$
\end_inset

 be a statistic, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a subset of the real line.
 Suppose that test procedure for the hypotheses (9.1.3) is of the form 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Then we call 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
test statistic
\series default
, and we call 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
rejection region 
\series default
of the test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a test is defined in terms of a test statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and rejection region 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, as in Definition 9.1.5, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}=\{x:r(x)\in R\}$
\end_inset

 is the critical region from Definition 9.1.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Typically, the rejection region for a test based on a test statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 will be some fixed interval or the outside of some fixed interval.
 For example, if the test rejects 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $T\ge c$
\end_inset

, the rejection region is the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[c,\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 Once a test statistic is being used, it is simpler to express everthing
 in terms of the test statistic in the rest of this book will be based on
 test statistics rather thant try to compute the critical region from Definition
 9.1.4.
 All of the tests in the test o fthis book will be based on test statistics.
 Indeed, most of the tests can be written in the form 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $T\ge c$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some theoretical arguments are given in Sections 9.2-9.4 for choosing certain
 test statistics in a variety of problems invlving a single parameter.
 Although these theoretical results provide optimal tests in the situations
 in which they apply many practical problem do not satisfy the conditions
 required to apply these results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Note: Dividing Both parameter space and sample space.
 
\series medium
In the various definitions given so far, the reader needs to keep straight
 two different divisions.
 First, we divided the parameter space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 into two disjoint subsets, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Next we divided the sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 into two disjoint subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 These divisions are related to each other, but the are not the same.
 For one things, the parameter space and the sample space usually are of
 different dimensions, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 will necessarily be different from 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The relation between the two divisions is the following: If the random
 sample 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 lies in the critical region 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

, then we reject the null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in S_{0}$
\end_inset

, we don't reject 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We eventually learn which set 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We rarely learn which set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
The Power Function and Types of Error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 stand for a test procedure of the form discussed earlier in this section,
 either based on a critical region or based on a test statistic.
 The interesting probabistic properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 can be summarized by computing, for each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\Omega$
\end_inset

, either the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\theta|\delta)$
\end_inset

 that the test 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 will reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 or the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\pi(\theta|\delta)$
\end_inset

 that it does not reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
9.1.6.
 Power Function.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 be a test procedure.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\theta|\delta)$
\end_inset

 is called the power function of the test 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 denotes the critical region of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, then the power function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\theta|\delta)$
\end_inset

 is determined by the relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(\theta|\delta)=Pr(X\in S_{1}|\theta)\text{ for }\theta\in\Omega\text{ (9.1.4)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is described in terms of a test statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and rejection region 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, the power function is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(\theta|\delta)=Pr(T\in R|\theta)\text{ for \ensuremath{\theta\in\Omega}\text{ (9.1.5)}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Since the power function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\theta|\delta)$
\end_inset

 specifies, for each possible value f the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 will reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

, it follows that the ideal power function would be one for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\theta|\delta)=0$
\end_inset

 for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\theta|\delta)=1$
\end_inset

 for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 .
 If the power function of a test 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 actually had these values, then regardless of the actual value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 would lead to correct decision with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 In a practical problem, however, there would seldom exist any test procedure
 having this ideal power function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the possibility of error exists in virtually every testing problem,
 we should consider what kinds of errors we might take.
 For each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, the decision to reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an incorrect decision.
 Similarly, for each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, the decision not to reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an incorrect decision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
9.1.7.
 Type 
\begin_inset Formula $I/II$
\end_inset

 Error.
 An erroneous decision to reject a true null hypothesis is 
\emph on
type I error, 
\emph default
or an error of the first kind.
 An erroneous decision not to reject a false null hypothesis is called a
 
\emph on
type II error 
\emph default
, or an error of the second kind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a need to strike an appropriate balance between the two goals of
 low power in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and high power in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most popular method for striking a balance between the two goals is
 to choose a number 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

 between 0 and 1 and require that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(\theta|\delta)\leq\alpha_{0},\text{ for all \ensuremath{\theta\in\Omega_{0}}(9.1.6)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then among all tests that satisfy (9.1.6), the statistician seeks a test whose
 power function is as high as can be obtained for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\in\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This method is discussed in Sections 9.2 and 9.3.
 Another method of balancng the proababilities of type I and type II errors
 is to minimize linear combination of the different probabilities of error.
 We shall discuss this method in Sec 9.2 and again in Sec.
 9.8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Note: Choosing Null and Alternative Hypotheses.
 
\series medium
If one chooses to balance type I and type II error probabilities by requiring
 (9.1.6), then one has introduced an asymmetry in the treatment of the null
 and alternative hypotheses.
 In mose testing problems, such asymmetry can be quite natural.
 Generally, one of the two errors (type I and type II) is more costly or
 less palatable in some sense.
 It would make sense to put tighter controls on the probability of the more
 serious error.
 For this reason, one generally arranges the null and alternative hypotheses
 so that type I error is the error most to be avoided.
 For cases in which neither hypotheseis is naturally the null, switch the
 names of null and alternative hypotheses can have a variety of different
 effects on the results of testing procedures.
 (see Exercise 21 in this section).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantities in Eq.
 (9.1.6) play a fundamental role in hypothesis testing and have special names.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
9.1.8.
 Level/Size.
 A test that satisfies (9.1.6) is called a level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

 test, and we say that the test has level of significance 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, the size 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\delta)$
\end_inset

 of a test 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha(\delta)=\sup_{\theta\in\Omega_{0}}\pi(\theta|\delta)\text{ (9.1.7)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice: It seems 
\series bold
threshold 
\series default
for probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following results are immediate consequences of Definition 9.1.8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary*
9.1.1.
 A test 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is a level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

 test if and only if its size is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\delta)\leq\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

).
 If the null hypothesis is simple, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:\theta=\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, then the size of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\delta)=\pi(\theta_{0}|\delta)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Making a Test Have a Specific Significance Level
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whenever we choose a test procedure, we should also examine the power function.
 If one has made a good choice, then the power function should generally
 be larger for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 than for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Also the power function should increase as 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 moves away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, Fig.
 9.4 shows plots of the power function for two of the example in this section.
 In both cases, the power function increase as the parameter moves away
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

