\begin_layout Definition*
9.3.2.
 Monotone Likelihood Ratio.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}(x|\theta)$
\end_inset

 denote the joint p.d.f.
 or the joint p.f.
 of the observations 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X_{1},...,X_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T=r(X)$
\end_inset

 be a statistic.
 It is said that the joint distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a monotone likelihod ratio (MLR) in the statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 if the following property is satisfied: For every two value 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}<\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

, the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}(x|\theta_{2})/f_{n}(x|\theta_{1})$
\end_inset

 depends on the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 only through the function 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)$
\end_inset

, and this ratio is a monotone function of 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)$
\end_inset

 over the range of possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Specifically, if the ratio is increasing, we say that the distribution
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has increasing MLR, and if the ratio is decreasing, we say that the distributio
n has decreasing MLR.
\end_layout

